            <bodyText><![CDATA[<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="pXvR-mdYREo" />


<p>The opening round of the season is always a nervous and
dangerous time. &nbsp;New drivers have been promoted from the
D-class series and are looking to make their mark in the Star
Mazdas. &nbsp;It's especially dangerous for me, I think.
&nbsp;Because of my lower iRating I'll likely get the new drivers
in my races until my iRating climbs high enough to get into the top
SOF (Strength of Field) race.&nbsp;</p>

<p>I started well, setting an ok qualifying time of 1:22.018, even
though I've done 1:21.7 in practice. &nbsp;My qualifying lap was
set on the 9th lap of that set of tyres, indicating perhaps I'm not
running enough tyre pressure and the tyres are not getting up to
working temperature fast enough.</p>

<p>Race 1, with a SOF of 1363, saw me start from pole with a margin
of 0.4s to second place. &nbsp;Unfortunately I was tapped coming
into turn 2, getting a 4x. &nbsp;Fortunately it didn't do any
damage and I continued on in first place, with 2nd running very
closely behind. &nbsp;</p>

<p>On lap 3 Matthew Bretten sitting in second place and who had
tapped me on lap 1 gave me another tap that this time spun me and I
got hit by another car, putting an end to my race and all up
collecting 10x incident points.</p>

<p><img src="/media/182/brandshatch-r1.jpg" width="800" height="346" alt="Brandshatch-r1"/></p>

<p><span>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p><span>Race 2 was less eventful. &nbsp;Again I started from pole
but this time I got a clean getaway and pulled a 30+ second lead by
the end of the race to win comfortably.</span></p>

<p><span><img src="/media/187/brandshatch-r2.jpg" width="800" height="390" alt="Brandshatch-r2"/></span></p>

<p><span>Race 3 was similar to Race 2 but even less eventful.
&nbsp;After an accident on lap 1 not far behind allowed me to get a
10s gap to second by the end of the lap, I was never headed.
&nbsp;As others come off, I kept driving consistently and took the
win by nearly a full minute.</span></p>

<p><img src="/media/192/brandshatch-r3.jpg" width="800" height="410" alt="Brandshatch-r3"/></p>

<p style="text-align: left;">The problem with my race efforts to
date was low Strength of Field. &nbsp;While it allowed me &nbsp;to
add to my win tally, low SOF races don't yield good championship
points, and that's where it's at for me. &nbsp;I needed to get a
high SOF, at least 1800. &nbsp;Race 4 was much better, with a
strength of fied of 2142. &nbsp;I just had to come to terms with
the very rapid duo of Mike Quayle and David Buda, also from
Australia.</p>

<p style="text-align: left;">Buda started from pole but lost a few
tenths at the first turn, allowing Quayle and myself to get by.
&nbsp;I stuck it round the outside of turn two in a got better
drive off the corner and the inside line to turn 3. &nbsp;From
there, Quayle pulled an eventual buffer of 6 seconds by the end of
the race. &nbsp;I had managed to extend the gap to Buda to 3
seconds but two mistakes on two laps in the middle of the race
meant Buda caught right back up and pushed me hard for the
remainder of the race.</p>

<p style="text-align: left;">But it wasn't enough and I had the
measure of him through a few critical corners, enough to hold
second place until the end, and a rewarding 121 chanpionship
points.</p>

<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="text-align: left;"><img src="/media/197/brandshatch-r4.jpg" width="800" height="388" alt="Brandshatch-r4"/></p>

<p style="text-align: left;"><span>I now sit second in the Division
4 championship table and 61st overall.</span></p>
]]></bodyText>
