            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>I've been wanting to race this track, my "home" circuit (being
the only iRacing circuit from Australia), since I started racing
here. &nbsp;It was never on the rotation for the Skip Barber, at
least not when I drove the Skippy. &nbsp;I've done a couple of
practice sessions here in the V8Supercar, but my lack of experience
in that car made the drive not so rewardining.</p>

<p>Phillip Island is a tricky circuit to get used to. &nbsp;The
first corner I found challenging, along with many of the others...
Anyway, the first corner on my "default" setup was a handful.
&nbsp;It looks like it can be taken flat but then once the car is
past the exit the back end steps out every time. &nbsp;A few setup
tweaks later and I was able to take it flat and then I was on to
the next challenge, turn 2! &nbsp;Turn 2 is a tightening left
hander that also is a little off camber, making it rather
challenging and especially so in the early stages of a race.
&nbsp;</p>

<p>I could go on and name most every corner here as a techincal
challenge, but for brevities sake I'll narrow it down. &nbsp;It
seemed a lot of drivers were having offs near the end of the lap,
where the track drops down sharpley and turns hard right.
&nbsp;Many people were braking too late and understeering off the
road. I learnt to brake early, before the crest of the hill.
&nbsp;It's probably done faster braking later, but for me, that
method kept my car stable every time. &nbsp;Try a few meters later
and I was inconsistent in my ability to get around the corner.
&nbsp;Better to be safe than sorry.</p>

<p><strong>Qualifying</strong></p>

<p>Thanks to a busy week with my birthday on Tuesday and the
on-again, off-again birth of my son, I didn't get as much time as
usual to iRacing this week. &nbsp;I qualified on Sunday morning 8am
and was happy enough with the time that I wanted to go racing
immediately.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="sqIchDQouEg" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Race 1</strong></p>

<p>The first race was a rather high SOF race (2800ish) and being
fresh and inexperienced I thought I'd start from the pits.
&nbsp;With such consistent and fast drivers it was hard to make
places. &nbsp;The only positive being I didn't lose any ground.
&nbsp;I had &nbsp;zero incidents during the race and perhaps if I
started where I qualified I'd have got a better haul of points.
&nbsp;Either way, it was an ok race, even it if was boring.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="CRqcYMDOpkE" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Race 2</strong></p>

<p>A decent race. I qualified 4th, with the my two usual sparring
partners ahead of me, David Buda and Mike Quayle. &nbsp;I enjoy
racing these two guys more than any other because they're just a
little bit faster than me and they always keep it clean. &nbsp;The
result is enjoyable racing and I usually go better for trying to
keep up with them.</p>

<p>I managed to jump David on the start and held him off for the
entire race, while Mike and Justin Lindsay raced off on a tight
battle of their own, eventually 10seconds down the road when the
flag dropped.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="OmCNpePbn9E"
/>]]></bodyText>
