          <umbBlogPost id="1150" parentID="1162" level="5" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1053" template="1046" sortOrder="1" createDate="2012-09-15T14:09:49" updateDate="2013-05-20T08:12:26" nodeName="A race or two around Suzuka" urlName="a-race-or-two-around-suzuka" writerName="Rob" creatorName="Rob" path="-1,1057,1083,1143,1162,1150" isDoc="">
            <closeComments>0</closeComments>
            <PostDate>2012-09-15T00:00:00</PostDate>
            <thumbnail>
            </thumbnail>
            <articleType>
            </articleType>
            <tags><![CDATA[star mazda,suzuka]]></tags>
            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>I don't mind me some Suzuka. &nbsp;It's not that I do well here;
I don't compared to some other tracks. &nbsp;It's more about Suzuka
being a real drivers track, like Spa. &nbsp;The Esses (3, 4, 5, 6,
7) in the first half of the lap require a well balanced car and a
smooth driving style. &nbsp;It's a challenge to string together a
great time in that section. &nbsp;But it's not just there, that
carries on to many corners of the track, including the two Degners
(8 &amp; 9) before you pass under the bridge, and especially the
mighty Spoon.</p>

<p><img src="/media/607/suzuka-trackmap.png" width="600" height="380" alt="Suzuka-trackmap" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"/></p>

<p>Much is spoken of 130R in Formula 1, but for me, one of the
hardest corners to get right not just on this track but on the
Calendar is Spoon (13). &nbsp;Spoon is the last coner before the
back straight that bleeds into 130R (14) and it requires
positioning the car exactly, if you want a good run down that
straight. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Another tough corner, where I can lose half a second in one
(two) corners it the chicane (15 &amp; 16) at the end of the lap.
&nbsp;Heavy braking with a bit of turning. &nbsp;There's easily
0.3s found in the corner by getting the brakes exactly right and
from my experience it's very hard to do consistently. &nbsp;In
fact, my fastest lap to date, 1:58.1 is an example of where I got
it right. &nbsp;I've managed a number of 1:58.3's, but I lose bulk
time in that corner every time.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Qualifying</strong></p>

<p>A decent enough session. &nbsp;My qualifying time ended up about
3/10ths of a second off my best lap time in practice, which is
pretty typical unfortunately. &nbsp;I could have tried to get
closer to that mark, but it probably wouldn't have made much
difference, in retrospect. &nbsp;</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="iB_oJe1q4cc" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Race 1</p>

<p>My first race at Suzuka for the season was the highest SOF race
of the week, a 2800+ race with some very fast drivers. I qualified
7th, just 0.06s behind David Buda, which brought a smile to my
face, because we tend to end up at about the same pace at most
tracks. &nbsp;True to form, we left the line neck and neck, with me
getting the jump on him off the line. &nbsp;He slid on turn one of
lap two but caught it, losing about 1 second but within a few laps
he was on the back of me again. Thankfully you need a good speed
difference to make a move here and the opportunities are scare.
&nbsp;He seemed to have my measure through turn one and two, but
you can't pass there, not on the outside anyway. &nbsp;At the
halfway mark Stanislav Shubin was about 7 seconds back, he'd gain a
couple of seconds but then lose them again, presumably making a
mistake. &nbsp;At lap 15 I'd been watching the gap between David
and Me, and Stanislav close pretty quickly and I started to get
worried about having only 2.1s deficit and 5 laps to try and
defend.</p>

<p>Going into turn 8 I thought I'd brake an few meters later and
try and get some more speed. &nbsp;I should have remembered the
pact I made to myself about 6 months ago: Don't try new shit in the
race, ever. &nbsp;I went a little bit too fast and into the turn
and consequently ran a little wide and lost the back end. &nbsp;I
spun and both David and Stanislav got by. &nbsp;The broken braked
Nathan Growden, who seems a bit hapless of late, wasn't a threat a
lap down, and I had no chance of recatching Stanislav on ruined
tyres so I cruised in, settling on keeping the car in one piece and
collecting a few points. &nbsp;</p>

<p>I realised before midway point that I didn't drop the pressures
in my tyres and that while giving me strong initial pace was
probably my undoing toward the end of the race. &nbsp;I corrected
the problem for future races.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="jdO7z20JPKA" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Race 2</strong></p>

<p>I was pumped for race two (10:30am on the Saturday). &nbsp;With
the fun of race 1 and the switch to lower pressure tyres I was
confident of a strong result and a fun race. &nbsp;It was a good
field and I qualified 5th. &nbsp;Alas, Nathan Growden had a
cracking start and took the inside into turn 1. &nbsp;In the replay
you can see me moving right to give him space, but it wasn't
enough. &nbsp;He got a wobble on on accelleration and ghost touched
me through turn 2 and we met in a collision that ended both our
races. &nbsp;In the replay it looks like he made contact with the
stalled car in front of him and that bent the right side of his
front wing, which would have changed the handling of his car.
&nbsp;Short but definitely not sweet.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="l2-NiCwa9Cg" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Race 3</strong></p>

<p>Nathan Growden was in the race too and at the start we had a
little joke about the last race and I mentioned in general that
it'd be nice to not have anyone crash at turn 1. Especially into
me.</p>

<p>I had a cracking start and gunned it past Mike Quayle off the
line and pulled right and alongside Scott Gray2. &nbsp;We touched
as we turned into turn 1 and at first I thought I caused a massive
pile up, as there was some serious carnage behind me. &nbsp;I felt
like a right twat in light of what I said on the grid. Once I got a
chance to look at the replay it seemed like Scott Gray2 turned into
me and hit my sidepod, which unsettled him and he took out Mike
Quayle. &nbsp; From there I had a 4 second gap to second which
eventaually turned into almost no gap at all as after 15 laps Scott
had hauled me back in. &nbsp;A positive was that Mike Quayle wasn't
catching me and was about a consistent 20 seconds behind.
&nbsp;</p>

<p>For about three laps Scott and I went at it with 0.3s seperating
us. &nbsp;Intense and I was getting increasing nervous about an
upcoming move. &nbsp;At least it's hard to pass around Suzuka and
Scott had the sense to not try and force something that was never
going to come off unless I made a mistake. &nbsp;Thankfully for me
his wheel stopped working with 3 laps to go and he crashed straight
into a wall. &nbsp;I cruised the last few laps and Mike Quayle
closed a second or so. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Looking back at the replay after the event, there's pretty much
no way Scott Gray would have seen me alongside if he didn't have
triple screens (I have triples, so my view is at least a bit
larger). &nbsp;Actually I guess if he was running an
insane-for-one-screen FOV he may have seen me... &nbsp;No hard
feelings on my part though (especially seeing as I won!).</p>

<p>That win means I've won at every track except Phillip Island
this season. I only ran two races at PI and the first one was a
3000 SOF where I started from the pits. &nbsp;Technically I haven't
won at Iowa either, but I didn't run there...</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="nM8dzhnB1Ok" />


<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Race 4</strong></p>

<p>A strange start. &nbsp;I got off the line ok but then going into
turn 1, Bram Den Boer, who started behind me shot up the inside and
across my nose and then off the track, taking out (thankfully) the
rapid Nenad Matijevic. From there, the entire race was about
examining Robert Ortons gearbox. &nbsp;Had I of qualified again,
with a time closer to my practice pace I'd have been in front of
Robert on the grid and would probably have finished third.
&nbsp;</p>

<p>I followed him within a second for literally the entire race,
bar about half a lap when I overcooked it into turn 11 and lost a
full second. &nbsp;I tried like heck with 2 laps to go but as was
the theme in other races this week, I wasn't able to pass. &nbsp;At
least the other two times it was others trying to pass me!</p>

<p>Crazy start antics ensues in the vid.</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="UPHYqH4LZk8"
/>]]></bodyText>
