          <umbBlogPost id="1281" parentID="1351" level="5" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1053" template="1046" sortOrder="1" createDate="2013-05-17T15:43:28" updateDate="2013-05-20T09:17:07" nodeName="Racecraft: Managing your tyres" urlName="racecraft-managing-your-tyres" writerName="Rob" creatorName="Rob" path="-1,1057,1083,1332,1351,1281" isDoc="">
            <closeComments>0</closeComments>
            <PostDate>2012-03-16T00:00:00</PostDate>
            <thumbnail>1288</thumbnail>
            <articleType>1261</articleType>
            <tags><![CDATA[]]></tags>
            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>A cars tires provide the interface between the power produced by
the engine, the downforce produced by the aerodynamics, the grip
produced by the springs, roll bars and other suspension components
and the road surface. &nbsp;In this role, tires play the most
important factor in car performance. &nbsp;Without tires a car
would go nowhere.</p>

<p>That said, there are no tire setup options with in Codemasters
F1 series other than the type of tyre that can be fitted to a car:
Option, Prime, Intermediate, Wet. Tires do degrade while driving
though.</p>

<p><strong>What causes a tire to lose performance?</strong></p>

<p>A tires' performance is lost as rubber is worn off during the
course of a race. &nbsp;You may think that higher grip situations
would result in higher tire wear. &nbsp;The tire is giving more
performance by way of grip, so surely it must do so at the cost of
life? &nbsp;This isn't case however. &nbsp;A tire is degrades
faster in low grip situations where the wheels are slipping over
the surface of the track. &nbsp;The tire has to work harder to get
traction as well as it's moving across the road faster than it
otherwise would, in the absence of wheelspin. &nbsp;If you're
getting 10% wheelspin over 30 meters of corner exit, your tire has
just done 33 meters.</p>

<p><strong>How can wheelspin be reduced?</strong></p>

<p>Wheelspin is caused by a lack of grip (see&nbsp;<a
href="/{localLink:1313}"
title="What is grip in and how is it generated on an F1 car">what
is grip and how it is generated</a>). &nbsp;Grip is produced by
either aerodynamical or mechanical means, or more typically both.
&nbsp;Applying more grip will produce a more driveable car.</p>

<p>Wheelspin is also reduced by being more sensitive with throttle
and brake inputs. &nbsp;Rather than instantly pushing the
accelerator to the floor, gently squeeze the throttle. &nbsp;This
will give you more grip, and while it may not feel as fast, it
generally is faster than rapidly applying the throttle. &nbsp;It
will also save you fuel. &nbsp;More gentle braking can also save
the life of the tire by reduce the chance of locking a wheel into a
turn and generating a flat spot, the opposite of wheel spin, where
the tyre is not moving as fast (it's not moving at all!) as the car
is across the surface of the track.</p>

<p>Generally, a higher downforce setting will yield reduced tire
wear. &nbsp;You can also adjust the gearing to give more traction,
which will help eliminate wheelspin. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Try various setups and driving styles as analyse the effect with
F1PerfView, recoding your lap with&nbsp;<a href="/{localLink:2104}"
title="Using F1Speed">F1Speed</a>.</p>
]]></bodyText>
