            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>As round four of the 2013 F1 championship kicks of today in
Bahrain and in the wake of the Chinese Grand Prix, I'm thinking
about the state of modern F1. &nbsp;Is F1 still what it used to be.
&nbsp;Is it drivers championship, where the fastest, smartest
driver wins? &nbsp;Is it a constructors championship, where the
best car wins? &nbsp;Was it ever about?</p>

<p>The constructors part is easy. &nbsp;The car construction brief
can be boiled down to 'Within the regulations of the day, buid the
car that scores the most points'. &nbsp;The team that does that
deserves the title in my opinion (assuming they've got drivers
sufficent to maximise the cars capabilities).</p>

<p>The drivers world championship is a little more complex.
&nbsp;Sure, the driver that accumulates the most points during a
season is 'best' driver. &nbsp;That driver has, better than his
peers, made use of environment in which he has to operate.
&nbsp;What annoys me is when things happen like they did in China.
&nbsp;The most striking comment I heard from a driver during that
race was from Jenson Button when he had to ask his team if he was
racing the car behind. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Yes, F1 has long been about strategy. When to push and when to
pace, about trading off speed against fuel consumption given the
time it takes to pit and refuel (in the days of refuelling) and
about ensuring your engine doesn't go bang. &nbsp;This new Pirelli
era has given us fans and the drivers something else. &nbsp;Tyre
wear is so bad that teams are running vastly different strategies
and drivers don't know who they're racing against because they
don't know what driver is on what strategy. &nbsp;There are
effectively 22 time trial events happening simulatenously on track
as each driver races against the clock. &nbsp;Drivers aren't
pushing all the time. &nbsp;Instead of having a 2 hour / 300 km
flat out sprint we've got a compressed 2 hour / 300 km endurance
race.</p>

<p>Hang on, part of the attraction of F1 for me is the strategy,
the "Moving Chess Game" they like to brand F1 when it gets
"boring". &nbsp;I'm actually a fan of the current format. &nbsp;I
like that I don't know who is going to be the victor. &nbsp;I
remember the Schumacher era still too painfully. &nbsp;The Red
Baron would bolt into the distance and it was a race for second
place. &nbsp;Those times were the only in my 25 plus years of
watching F1 where I struggled to maintian interest watching races
in the middle of the night (here in Australia). &nbsp;Now I can't
fall asleep because the current leader being the race winner is not
a foregone conclusiong. &nbsp;Being an Australian (and therefore I
sort of have to support Webber - plus I like the guy) that means
there's always hope. &nbsp;It's possible my driver could mount a
late race charge, or that drivers further up the field could drop
back as their tyres "fall off the cliff". &nbsp;I've also long been
a big fan of the constructors side of it. The guys on the pitwall
and in the factory are the real superstars. &nbsp;F1 now more than
ever is a team sport. There's no way a driver can keep tabs on
every driver in the field, as far as their strategies go.
&nbsp;Drivers need their support crew. &nbsp;Gone are the days of
grabbing the fastest driver and plugging him into your car and
collecting the wins (contrary to what I just said, part of me cried
as I wrote that).</p>

<p>We're also now seeing more action than ever. &nbsp;Yes its fake
action in some cases, and I think this season with generally two
DRS zones there will be artificial overtaking, but it's better than
those Schumacher dominance days.</p>

<p>After the second half of last season I thought 2012 was going to
be unique. &nbsp;I thought we wouldn't see multiple race winners at
the start of the season. &nbsp;Thankfully we've got that again in
2013. &nbsp;What I think we will see though is the same set of few
(3 or 4) winners take wins at different circuits for at least the
first half of the season, and probably beyond. &nbsp;With 2014
engine changes getting ever close teams will invariably start to
shift their focus. &nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></bodyText>
            <teaser><![CDATA[
<p>As round four of the 2013 F1 championship kicks of today in
Bahrain and in the wake of the Chinese Grand Prix, I'm thinking
about the state of modern F1. &nbsp;Is F1 still what it used to be.
&nbsp;Is it drivers championship, where the fastest, smartest
driver wins?</p>
]]></teaser>
