            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>I've just completed my debut week in the McLaren MP4/12C as a GT
racer and I'm satisfied. &nbsp;</p>

<p>My goal for this week was simply to finish the week with
confidence in the car; confidence that with me behind the wheel,
the car wouldn't spear off the track seemingly randomly. &nbsp;I
wasn't concerned with competitiveness and was toying with the idea
of starting from pit-lane, just to ensure I didn't over do it.
&nbsp;As it turned out I didn't need to because other drivers
helped me start from pitlane...</p>

<p>I practice all during the week, starting on Tuesday with no
confidence the car. &nbsp;I couldn't get the thing to the apex
without the back end stepping out on me. &nbsp;Almost every corner
in qualifying trim was like that, and the car wasn't much better
with race fuel onboard. &nbsp;I sought guidance from my teammates
at Vortex and tried alterting the diff lock and shifting weight
rearward but still to no effect. &nbsp;A big thing was the physical
braking didn't feel "right". &nbsp;As any driver will tell you, if
they're not confident with the feel of the car, they have no basis
to build performance on.</p>

<p>Thursday night, after making no progress with my apex attitude,
I pulled my pedals out, relubed them and set them up for proper
left foot braking, including significantly reducing the throw of
the brake.</p>

<p>Instantly the car was easier to handle and my apex problem was
solved. &nbsp;Finally I could start working with the car proper,
and building up to a fast lap. &nbsp;Strangely I didn't get any
faster, just more consistent. &nbsp;I must have fluked in that one
super lap with the old pedal set. I did beat it on Saturday, but
only by 0.04s, to do a 1:22.709.</p>

<p>Saturday morning qualifying and I spent the entire 20 minutes
laying down times. First with the race fuel load and then with
qualifying load, using the unmodified team Q set (which JCG the
team captain had taken to a 1:22.275). &nbsp;My best time was a
1:23.089. &nbsp;Not bad and not my best ever time. &nbsp;I've
rarely gone sub 1:23.0 so I didn't bother trying qualifying again.
&nbsp;Instead I started my race campaign.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Race 1</h3>

<p>I qualified 2nd on the grid (of the Mclarens) and to my surprise
found that this series uses a rolling start. Something new to me.
&nbsp;Approaching the corkscrew on the warmup lap, the corvette in
front of me came to a complete stop. &nbsp;I hit the brakes and
tapped him and the car behind me slammed into my rear. &nbsp;My car
was instantly bent out of shape. The pits were closed on the warmup
lap so I had to do another tour and then pit. &nbsp;After a 8
minute stop I came out 6 laps down and the pressure was off for any
decent performance. &nbsp;I did manage to claw back a few places
through attrition, and I didn't get any more incidents, to finish
in 5th place.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Race 2</h3>

<p>I toyed with the idea of starting from the pits but instead
elected to start from my 3rd place on the grid. &nbsp;The two cars
in front of me both qualified with 1:22.2's so I didn't hold any
chance for the race. &nbsp;On the end of the warmup lap the 2nd
place car made a mistake and by turn 1 of lap 1 I was in second but
ran wide through turn 1. &nbsp;I held it together but it was enough
for that car to come back up the inside. &nbsp;He lost control of
the rear under accelation from that turn and tapped me then knifed
across my front and put me straight into the wall. &nbsp;A few
tentative laps (and many lost places) and I got used to the
handling of my car, and was able to lap in the 1:25's consistnetly
(about 1.5s off my undamaged race pace). &nbsp;Again I made no more
incidents and managed to bring the car home in 6th place (after
falling down to 14th).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Race 3</h3>

<p>Again I started 3rd. &nbsp;This time I made it past the warmup
and first lap. &nbsp;On lap 2 I was again hit as 4th place
accelarated out of the last corner and tried to pass me on the
outside. Fortunately for him he lost his rear on acceleration but
had me to bounce off. &nbsp;Unfortunately for me I was put nose
first into the pit straight wall. &nbsp;I recovered many places
down, with a badly damaged front end and no bonnet but my car felt
ok. &nbsp;It felt more consistent than the previous two races.
&nbsp;</p>

<p>I had a few spins and three slow downs after accidentally
cutting the corkscrew. &nbsp;I fought my way back to up what would
have been 5th place except I lost control on the last corner of the
race and stopped parked in the middle of the road. &nbsp;The 2nd
place driver came to put a lap on me but hit he Corvette in front
of him who had hit me as I tried to recover. &nbsp;My fault :(
&nbsp;I eventually claimed another 6th place.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Race 4</h3>

<p>Finally I had a race where I didn't get badly damaged on the
opening laps. &nbsp;I did however have a few spins of my own this
time. &nbsp;I again started in 3rd place. &nbsp;I got caught out a
multiple times when I had to let Corvettes by, but that's all part
of the fun :) &nbsp; I had a few troubles with lapped MP4 drivers
not getting out of the way but overall the mistakes were my own
fault and I enjoyed some good racing. &nbsp;Again I finished
6th.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Race 5</h3>

<p>I don't normally race late on a Sunday (8pm) but my wife asked
me if I was going to race, so I took that as her saying she had
stuff she wanted to do so I should go race. &nbsp;So I did. &nbsp;I
started from 8th position in a field of about 25 Mclarens, the
biggest MP4 contigent yet that also include teammate Cyril Floris.
I was up to fourth position for a good while before a few self
induced spins and a slow down through the corkscrew. &nbsp;I also
got spun off track when I back marker I was lapping decided to try
and retake the position and bombdived me. &nbsp;Annoying, as I'd
closed in on him at 2 seconds a lap only to have him try to repass
at the corner after I took him.. &nbsp;Heading for 3rd place I came
round the corner up the hill toward the corkscrew but lost the back
end and went headfirst into the tyre barrier. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>I reversed out and got going again, having lost two places (one
of the people to pass was Cyril) and I gave chase again. &nbsp;I
started closing on both the two drivers who got by but made another
mistake. &nbsp;Then I'd close up again. &nbsp;I eventually finished
in another 6th place (lol!) after spinning from 5th on the last lap
after closing down a 6 second gap to Cyril to only 1.5s.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Overall</h3>

<p>I had a good fun weekend. I was annoyed by the number of times I
got taken out by other drivers. &nbsp;Overall the drivers seems to
be more careful off the start line, which was great. Normally I'm
the one being overly cautious but in that last race I was going
much slower than what I'd like but didn't want to try and pass and
have us both (or more people) off. &nbsp;I also some some pretty
dodgy driving from guys in front. &nbsp;Moves I would consider
overly aggressive. &nbsp;That said, there were a number of nice
drivers who played the smart long game and would leave racing room.
&nbsp;Good to see.</p>

<p>As I stated in my goal for the week, I just wanted to get a feel
for the car and I not only managed that, I found I also had decent
car speed.</p>
]]></bodyText>
