            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p><img src="/media/3757/Sebring-International.JPG" width="500" height="335" alt="Sebring-International.JPG" style="float: left;"/></p>

<p>I don't mind me some Sebring action, even if I haven't spent a
lot of time here. &nbsp;I figured the circuit should lend itself
well to overtaking, with the wide (in places) track. &nbsp;Many of
the corners are quite difficult, meaning people will be coming off
a lot.</p>

<p>This week didn't turn out to be the big jump in iRating I was
expecting. &nbsp;Mid week I found the fun of MX-5's at Laguna Seca.
&nbsp;I did a few races in that car there and saw my SR drop a bit
but my iRating increase by about 200. &nbsp;</p>

<h4>Practice</h4>

<p>As usual I started practice on Tuesday night and started turning
some decent lap times. &nbsp;Nothing blindingly quick but I was
down in the 2:02's after about an hour or two.</p>

<p>Later in the week I managed to do a 2:01.9, with an optimal of
2:01.0. &nbsp;Not the fastest in world, or even my team, but fast
enough to get some good results, top 5's in the races.</p>

<h4>Qualifying</h4>

<p>I didn't get to qualifying until Saturday morning and it was
heart-breaking. &nbsp;I had a number of off's during the 20 minute
period, and a number of 1x's at turn 7. &nbsp;Starting my final
qualifying lap, I nailed turn 1 and was 0.1 up on my optimal time
and 0.4 up on my PB, through the first corner alone. &nbsp;It got
better. By the time I got to turn 7 I was 0.8s up on my personal
best. &nbsp;Then disaster. &nbsp;After seeing how far in front I
was, I as usual I tightened up. &nbsp;This caused me to mistake
into T7 and I got a 1x on the inside of the turn. &nbsp;I
hesistated for a moment and then thought 'You know what, I'll keep
going hard and see what I can do'. Pushing hard, I crossed the line
with a 2:00.8, my fastest ever lap and better than my previous
optimal. It would have put me in the top 20 in the world. &nbsp;But
my "banker lap" was the only one that countered, a 2:03.2!</p>

<h4>Race</h4>

<p><img src="/media/4326/sebring-mp4-races.jpg" alt="2013s2w4"/></p>

<p>Racing certainly didn't go as planned. &nbsp;My first race was
an unmitigated disaster. &nbsp;I started 6th in a huge field and
lost it on the last corner of the first lap. From there I dropped
back to be third last, after luckily avoiding anyone else. &nbsp;I
started my charge back up the field and made short work of the Ford
GT's in front of me. &nbsp;I closed up behind the Mclarens but then
lost control of my car again, and again, and again. &nbsp;It seemed
each time I closed the gap down to trio of Qiang Gao, Manu
Heikkila, and Matt Malone. &nbsp;Matt (black and blue Ford GT) was
in the Ford GT but he was flying, as best he could anyway.
&nbsp;Time and again he'd nail me out of the last turn and I'd
battle to get by the rest of the lap. &nbsp;Good fun.</p>

<p>Qian Gao was bad though. &nbsp;He was all over the road braking
early, going slow through the corners, baulking. &nbsp;After the
race I see he has an iRating of 1095, so I'm not really surprised.
&nbsp;He had decent pace when he could keep it on the track (his
race PB was 2.1 seconds less than mine), just he couldn't keep it
on track very often (He is the green car in my video below).
&nbsp;Manu was fine, just not so fast (the Pink car). &nbsp;</p>

<p>At one point I was right behind Gao, with the leaders coming to
put us a lap down. &nbsp;In my desire to both not lose time and not
wreck the leaders I went up in the inside of Gao (see video). At
the time I thought I'd hit him and I pulled to the right and slowed
down to let him past. &nbsp;Watching the replay after the race I
didn't even come close.</p>

<p>The race was so bad from a POV of me making mistakes that I had
to record it. &nbsp;</p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO videourl="16CuajpkgSA" videoheight=""
aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0" videowidth=""
macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer" videoid="" /> 

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Race 2 didn't fair much better. &nbsp;My own teammate spun on
the last corner of the warmup lap triggering a four car collision
that included me. &nbsp;I was able to get going with no noticeable
change in car handling, but I'd slipped down the field. &nbsp;I
started making places up when I noticed a Ford GT catch and pass me
down the straight. &nbsp;That's not right and I looked down at my
pedal readout. &nbsp;I had the throttle pressed flat to the floor
and iRacing was registering only 75%. &nbsp;No wonder the Ford
could pass me. &nbsp;I battle with that for half a lap before
decided to pull the pedals out and plug back in, hopeflly fixing
the problem. &nbsp;I unfortunately pulled the wheel out and when I
plugged it back in I had lost all firmness in the wheel. &nbsp;This
made the force feedback more pronounced and it made the car hard to
drive straight. &nbsp;When I reset the pedals I had a weirdly
functioning brake, so I had to do it again. &nbsp;By now I was 45s
down from 2nd last and the car was weacing all over the road down
the straight and I started to collect a lot of 1x. &nbsp;I pulled
over and retired.</p>

<p>All I wanted was a good clean race where I didn't make stupid
mistakes, or others didn't make errors that impacted me. &nbsp;In
race 3 I got it. &nbsp;I made a clean start and waited my time
before passing cars. The 4 cars that finished ahead of me were all
faster, so 5th was as good as it was going to get. &nbsp;I finished
the race satisfied.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>In retrospect and as my team captain pointed out, I shouldn't
have raced the MX-5's this week and should have instead focussed on
practicing at Sebring. Sebring is not a track I'm overly familiar
with from previous experience in other cars.</p>
]]></bodyText>
