            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p><img src="/media/4470/blue_flag_sticker_front_bumper.jpg" width="460" height="258" alt="blueflagslim" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"/></p>

<p>Anyone who's participated in multi-class racing on iRacing knows
the pain of overtaking and being overtaken by cars in another
class, especially when it comes to going a lap down.</p>

<p>I get that the faster car doesn't want to get impeded by the
slower car and is impatient to get by. &nbsp;But also, the slower
car doesn't want to have his race ruined by have to excessively
slow down or go offline to help out the faster car. &nbsp;Respect
and sportsmanship go both ways here. &nbsp;There is an official
stance on this, Blue Flags.</p>

<p>Blue Flags are shown to the car when the car is about to be
lapped. &nbsp;In some real life motorsport categories the blue flag
is not used at all, in others such as F1, ignoring a blue flag will
get you a trip to the stewards. It's in the rules.&nbsp;</p>

<p>What does iRacing's official F.I.R.S.T. sporting code have to
say on this matter? &nbsp;</p>

<blockquote>
<p><em><strong>Section 6.5 - Blue Flag (blue with diagonal yellow
stripe)</strong></em></p>

<p><em>Indicates faster cars are approaching. <strong>This flag is
informational only</strong>. In all cases, it is the responsibility
of the faster car to safely overtake the slower car. It is the
responsibility of the slower car to maintain a consistent line. It
is strongly &nbsp;recommended that a slower car being lapped makes
every reasonable effort to facilitate a safe pass.</em></p>
</blockquote>

<p>The above is verbatim from the official rules. &nbsp;Keep in
mind blue flags are only ever shown to a car that is about to be
lapped by another car. &nbsp;Blue flags are not shown when a car in
a faster class is approaching a car in slower class in a fight for
race position.</p>

<p>What does this mean? &nbsp;I'm an MP4-12C driver in the GT
Challenge series, where I'm racing against Corvette ZR-1's in the
same field.</p>

<p><em>In all cases, it is the responsibility of the faster car to
safely overtake the slower car -&nbsp;</em> As a Corvette
approaches to lap me, at about 1.5 seconds out a blue flag is shown
to me, informing me the faster car is close behind.
&nbsp;Officially I need not alter my behaviour at all. &nbsp;The
Corvette must only overtake when it is safe to do so. &nbsp;</p>

<p>It is the responsibility of the slower car to maintain a
consistent line - As the Corvette approaches me I am maintain my
racing line. &nbsp;I am not to pull off to the side of the track to
allow the Corvette easy and safe passage. &nbsp;I am not to block
the Corvette by altering my line. &nbsp;If I maintain a consistent
line, the Corvette can more accurately assess when it is safe to
overtake, as is their responsibilty made clear in the previous
sentence of the regulations. &nbsp;These are the only two clearly
state responsibilities of the involved parties. &nbsp;</p>

<p>This means if I maintain my line any damage done to me by the
faster Corvette is the fault of the Corvette's. &nbsp;</p>

<p><em>It is strongly recommended that a slower car being lapped
make every reasonable effort to facilitate a pass -&nbsp;</em> Note
this is a recommendation. It is not something that must be
undertaken by a car being lapped. &nbsp;Any 'recommendation' falls
under a "sporting" action. &nbsp;As a participant in a sport, and
not be an arsehole, I want to make sure that I don't ruin a
Corvette drivers race by impeding him. &nbsp;Given the two
requirements above - and that the slower car must maintain a
consistent line, the only other action I can take facilitate a safe
pass is to reduce my speed. &nbsp; It's not safe to reduce speed
mid corner, as unexpectedly changing vehicle dynamics may cause
either to car to spin, so that leaves slowing down on straights,
yet staying on-line.</p>

<p>The main take-away from this is that faster cars should approach
a slower car as if blue flags don't exist, and be pleasantly
surprised when a slower car takes action to make it easier for a
faster car to overtake.</p>

<p>What do you think?</p>
]]></bodyText>
