            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p><img src="/media/3727/RoadAmerica-Road.JPG" width="500" height="315" alt="RoadAmerica-Road.JPG" style="float: left;"/>In the past, in other series especially the Star
Mazda, I have performed well at Road Ameria. &nbsp;My expectation
was that I'd perform well here again. &nbsp;I guess I ended up
doing ok...</p>

<p>It wasn't that I did poorly, it's just, well, as usual, I could
have done better. &nbsp;</p>

<p>My mindset this week was one of safety and steady collection of
iRating. &nbsp;I went in willing to give away positions to save
gain overall, rather than battling and losing. &nbsp;</p>

<h4>Practice</h4>

<p>I started the week struggling to get below 2:07.5, which I'd
done on Tuesday. I grabbed a set from my teammates and that helped
a little and I was able to just below and do a 2:06.9 in practice.
I practiced through the rest of the week, including the weekend,
just chipping away, but the fastest guys were doing high 2:04's and
low 2:05's. I struggled on race trim and that was the biggest
worry. 2:07's were hard to come-by. Whereas my teammates were often
dipping into the low 2:07's. I practiced a bunch with race fuel but
it didn't make a whole lot of difference.</p>

<h4>Qualifying</h4>

<p>I did the one session and pounded around getting faster and
faster until I scored a 2:06.754. I tried another 2 laps but didn't
get any quicker, making a few small mistakes instead.</p>

<p><img src="/media/5432/qra.jpg" alt="MP4-s2013w8-q"/></p>

<h4>Race</h4>

<p>Race 1 was interesting. I qualified 5th and my thinking was that
I'd cruise around and collect some points, with Wendel Parra ahead
and the crazy Diego Rancano Boudon nearby, as well as a few other
drivers higher ranked than me starting behind me. &nbsp;I got away
ok and fortunately, Boudon, being the knob-globbler that his is (<a
href="/{localLink:1248}" title="Respected Racers">yes I don't like
him</a>) jumped ahead before the race proper got underway, by way
of going faster than is polite in behind the pace car and before
the lights went green after the pace car pulled off. &nbsp;He
charged through two places but collided with 3rd place Julien
Deroche on lap 3, setting Deroche back to the pits for 2 laps,
while he only managed to recover 2 seconds behind me, now in 4th.
&nbsp;</p>

<p>Boudon was looking like pushing past so I let him past early and
as I did that Paul Darling got by too. &nbsp;I spent the rest of
the race with 3.0s of Darling, and sometimes as low as 0.3s!</p>

<p>True to forth, the dangerous Boudon collided with Wendel Parra
near the closing stages of the race and now I was in third place.
At the time I was 0.4 behind Darling and the distraction cost me
over two seconds, as the two ranted at each other over voice.
&nbsp;I caught up behind Darling on the last lap and was in with a
shot. On the last corner he ran wide, but I wasn't paying too much
attention, and forgot to shift down another gear. &nbsp;As a
result, I ran wide (I realised but too late) and my exit was
comprised. &nbsp;In the end we were 0.2 seconds apart as we crossed
the line. &nbsp;I was happy with 3rd and I scored my highest ever
points haul.</p>

<p>Race 2 should have been mine. &nbsp;I qualified on pole, with
Stev Buchheim behind me, but 0.4 back. &nbsp;He got racey as the
race started and tapped my rear left into turn 1. That cost him a
bit of time and he lost two places, retiring a few laps later
(though not through the contact with me). &nbsp; I quickly pulled
3.0 seconds on 2nd and 3rd as I caught the Corvettes in front, with
4 seconds to them. &nbsp;Then disaster for them and they collided.
&nbsp;With only two Vettes in the field I was left leading the race
outright for the first time! &nbsp;I got 5 laps in before I put
myself out. &nbsp;I was watching the gap back to Larry Smith in
2nd, and despite me pulling a gap early on, I was unable to pull
after the two Vettes collided and I had to come to a near stop to
miss them as they flipped through the air. &nbsp;I decided to push.
&nbsp;The first corner after my brain said "push", my back end hit
a curb and I was off, spinning down the grassy hill. &nbsp;I
recovered though, in third but I never got another look in at the
win. &nbsp;I at least gained 4 seconds on the leader between that
point and the end of the race, and 14 seconds on 2nd place. &nbsp;I
should have won.</p>

<p>Race 3 and I was in a strong field. &nbsp;Looking at the grid I
was 5th but I decided 8th would be good enough (out of 11). Off the
line I got away strong and we front running 5 cars pulled a 6
second gap back to 6th quickly. &nbsp;The leader, Manu Heikkila,
who averages 32 races a week since joining 3 months ago, spun off
and I was up in 4th and then 3rd. He came back at me quickly and I
went to let him through before he tagged me off and I lost 24
seconds. &nbsp;</p>

<p>I was making my way solidly back up through the field, closing
in on 6th through to 4th, when I came across a spun 6th position
car. &nbsp;We collided and my race was done while he drove off.</p>

<p>On both occasions, neither driver said sorry, even though
certianly in the second case he was most definitely at fault.
&nbsp;That annoys me. &nbsp;</p>

<p><img src="/media/5437/rra.jpg" alt="MP4-s2013w8-r"/></p>

<?UMBRACO_MACRO
videourl="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZEn5UF6BmuM"
videoheight="" aspectratio="" allowfullscreen="0"
videowidth="" macroAlias="uTube.ClassicPlayer"
videoid="" />]]></bodyText>
