            <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>With a new season now started I have set forth some goals and
hopefully a way forward with my performance.</p>

<p>Last season I competed in the GT challenge series, where
Corvettes CR6's were pitted against Mclaren MP4-12C's and Ford
GT's. &nbsp;This season iRacing has (correctly) dropped the GT
Challenge series, leaving a single series for each of those three
makes. While the Corvette and Ford will race the GT Prototype
series with the Honda HPD, the Mclaren will race in the Grand Am
series with the Riley Prototype cars. &nbsp;I think this is a much
better solution, as it should ensure enough numbers in each.
&nbsp;Mclaren being by far the most popular car of all those
mentioned.</p>

<p>The Grand Am series also streams the Thursday 8:45pm SOF race in
Australia. Meaning there's always a large turnout and multiple
splits. This is good for me as it means I can get my main racing
done before the weekend, even if it does mean I am a little
under-prepared.</p>

<p>After my rookie season in the MP4-12C last season I have
identified some points where I'd like to improve. &nbsp;Some I
gained from reading Ross Bentley's speed secrets and others I
observed on myself after numerous races.</p>

<p><strong>Things I do well</strong></p>

<ol>
<li>Qualify and lay down quick laps. &nbsp;While not the fastest, I
generally qualifying in the top 3 and my practices times are
good.</li>

<li>Leave appropriate racing room for other drivers. &nbsp;</li>

<li>Develop a stable setup.</li>

<li>Let drivers who are clearly faster go past me as soon as
practicle.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Problem Areas</strong></p>

<ol>
<li>I don't drive a defensive enough line during races. &nbsp;This
encourages other drivers to basically bombdive me, thanks to my
preference for late apexes making it look like I've left an
opening. &nbsp;I need to decisively show the driver behind there is
no chance to come through cleanly.</li>

<li>Race nerves are a huge problem for me. &nbsp;I struggle to keep
my hands and feet from shaking me off the track when starting in a
field I know will be difficult, or when there are drivers around my
speed nearby.&nbsp;</li>
</ol>

<p>Besides generally being not fast enough, the above two problem
areas are the main things keeping my iRating low. &nbsp;I'll build
up iRating only to have it brought crashing back down again.
&nbsp;I would really like to have a smaller gap between my average
qualifying position and my average race position. &nbsp;It's likely
the two will never be equal, given a DNF can sometimes mean I
finish a race in 20th or worse position, really ruining the
average. &nbsp;</p>

<p>I think the key to bringing these two average closer together is
to run a "race line" that is different than my "qualifying line"
when there are cars near me. &nbsp;At least on turn in.
&nbsp;Nerves can be reduced by lowering expectations. &nbsp;I have
qualified high up in some big races but I didn't rate myself and
thus my nerves were lower. &nbsp;I need to not go into every race
thinking it's my right to finish in the top few positions. &nbsp;
At least not for a while. &nbsp;</p>
]]></bodyText>
