    <umbTextpage id="1186" parentID="1057" level="2" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1055" template="1050" sortOrder="7" createDate="2013-04-12T14:17:59" updateDate="2013-08-06T09:12:39" nodeName="About" urlName="about" writerName="Rob" creatorName="Rob" path="-1,1057,1186" isDoc="">
      <bodyText><![CDATA[
<p>Ragged Racing is my motorsport blog. &nbsp;I'm a big fan of
simracing, in particular iRacing, as well as a fan of real world
Formula 1 and V8Supercars. &nbsp;I also play a number other sim
driving games.</p>

<h3>Sim Racing History</h3>

<p>My love of Formula 1 and sim racing dates back to Accolades
Grand Prix, which also got me interested in the real Formula 1.
&nbsp;It all started age 12, with my friends and I, trying to
out-do one another on that game in our lunch time of Grade 8 at our
local highschool. &nbsp;We'd all go and play on the
monochrome-green 8086 computers in our schools' lab. &nbsp;I wanted
to win so I practice on my grandmothers PC on weekends and during
the holidays (we didn't have our own) and soon I was fastest.</p>

<p>While I played Geoff Crammonds entire Grand Prix series
(Microprose), I attribute Grand Prix 2 as the defining game of,
well, I guess my life. &nbsp;I played Grand Prix 2 every day after
school. &nbsp;I'd spend extensive time just turning practice lap
after lap, collecting data to analyse in the games telemetry
viewer. &nbsp;I downloaded packs and hacks and addons from the
Internet. &nbsp;Back then it was still just keyboard too. &nbsp;It
wasn't until Grand Prix 3 that I got my first wheel.</p>

<p>I took a long break from sim-racing in the late 1990's and
through the 2000's as I completed highschool, went to uni (two
undergraduate degrees, a half finished post-graduate degree, and a
diploma) and established my career. &nbsp;</p>

<p>I wanted to return to sim-racing but I was waiting for a title
that would give me a similar experience to Microprose Grand Prix.
&nbsp;I had a played with Live for Speed and rFactor but didn't
have the time to invest (and I spent nearly 7 years playing World
of Warcraft as my sole game). &nbsp;When I heard Codemasters was
about to release F1 2010 I ponied up for a new pc and racing wheel
(Logitech G27) and went racing. &nbsp;</p>

<p>I raced in a F1 201x league for versions F1 2010 and F1 2011,
and someone in that league put me onto iRacing in early 2011.
&nbsp;I immediately fell in love with the feel of the cars, even
though I was only racing the Mazda MX-5/Miata. &nbsp;But I was
committed to my F1 201x league, maintaining the website, recording
scores, etc and iRacing was only fallback, for a quick thrash
between seasons of the league I was in. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Early 2012 I exitted the F1 201x league (admittedly acrimonously
but at least it meant there was no way back - and that's what I
wanted, to focus on my next step of sim racing). &nbsp;I started
poking around the iRacing site more and found out how championships
and seasons work, how points are scored and all that stuff.
&nbsp;Before this I never even knew points were tallied toward a
season champion!</p>

<p>Now I'm all in and iRacing is a fantastic platform for virtual
racing and competing. &nbsp;Near as perfect as it can get online
(yes, the physics can be further improved - but as an overall
platform - awesome).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

