<h3>Car Setup</h3>

<ul>
<li>Use negative and positive camber to ensure your tyres are
getting the most tread possible onto the road surface during
cornering.</li>

<li>Increased positive castor will cause increased negative camber
on the outside wheel during turning. &nbsp;Adjust the two in
tandem. &nbsp;Increased positive castor makes the steering more
heavy. &nbsp;Never use negative castor.</li>

<li>Generally, front toe-in causes the car to understeer on initial
turn in. &nbsp;Front toe-out has the opposite effect, causing
initial oversteer. &nbsp;Remember this is only on initial turn in
not mid corner or on the exit.</li>

<li>The lower the ride height the better, providing the car doesn't
bottom out or reduce suspension travel. &nbsp;Adjusting the 'rake'
(the difference between the front and rear ride heights) is done to
fine tune handling.</li>

<li>Try to run the softest possible rear springs and set the front
springs to balance the car after the rear is set. &nbsp;Harder
front springs will reduce weight transfer speed under braking and
therefore oversteer.</li>

<li>Tyres give up the most grip between 180 and 220 Fahrenheit (82
- 104 Celcius). &nbsp;</li>

<li>Temperature difference between the front and rear tyres
indicate a balance problem. &nbsp;Hotter fronts and the car is
understeering. &nbsp;Hotter rears and you may be getting too much
wheelspin out of corners. &nbsp;Keep tyre temperatures basically
equal on all four tyres.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Driving Fast</h3>

<ul>
<li>Positions are not made in corners, they are made on the
straights.</li>

<li>The secret to a fast lap lies in the corners because this
effects straight line speed (see previous point). &nbsp;The most
important corner on a track is the fastest corner leading on to a
straight. &nbsp;The least important corner is the slow speed corner
leading to another corner. &nbsp;Always prioritorise corners
leading onto straights.</li>

<li>Use the entire track when cornerning. &nbsp;The larger the
radius, the more speed can be carried through a corner.</li>

<li>Firstly master the ideal racing line</li>

<li>Secondly master the acceleration phase of the corner.</li>

<li>Thirdly master the braking into a corner, braking as late as
possible</li>

<li>Finally master carrying mid corner speed. Master these in
order.</li>
</ul>
]]></bodyText>
